      "avalancheActivity": {
        "comment": "As a consequence of new snow and a strong to storm force wind, extensive wind slabs will form in all aspects. These can be released easily. or in isolated cases naturally, above the tree line. Caution is to be exercised in particular at the base of rock walls and behind abrupt changes in the terrain, as well as adjacent to ridgelines and in gullies and bowls. Mostly avalanches are medium-sized. <br/> <br/> Additionally in isolated cases avalanches can penetrate near-ground layers of the snowpack and reach large size in isolated cases, especially on west, north and east facing slopes above approximately 2200 m, and on south facing slopes at elevated altitudes. <br/> <br/> Shooting cracks when stepping on the snowpack can indicate the danger.",
        "highlights": "Wind slabs represent the main danger. Weakly bonded old snow is to be evaluated with care and prudence."
